to put one dollar in each of the
jars.

45:31.529 --> 45:34.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BETH KOBLINER: That's very
interesting. Why
did you do that?

45:34.999 --> 45:38.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHILD: Because I want to do all,
all three
in here.

45:38.536 --> 45:40.104 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BETH KOBLINER: In savings? Wow.

45:40.137 --> 45:42.306 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And what are you
saving for?

45:42.340 --> 45:44.275 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHILD: College. College and high
school.

45:44.308 --> 45:50.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Teaching kids to
save, says Kobliner,
was just teaching them to wait,
as in the

45:50.982 --> 45:52.850 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
famous marshmallow experiment.

45:52.883 --> 45:57.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: All right, here's the
deal. Marshmallow
for you. You can either wait,
and I will give

45:57.822 --> 46:01.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you another one if you wait. You
can either
eat it right now, or you can
wait. Either

46:01.225 --> 46:02.193 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
way.

46:02.226 --> 46:04.195 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: We ran our own
mental version.

46:04.228 --> 46:09.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Suppose I had a marshmallow in
front of you
now and I said, if you don't eat
it for 15

46:09.033 --> 46:10.001 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
minutes...

46:10.034 --> 46:11.836 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHILD: I would eat it.

46:11.869 --> 46:15.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: You would eat it
right away,
even though I say I would give
you two later?

46:15.339 --> 46:16.607 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
CHILD: Mm-hmm.

46:16.641 --> 46:17.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: You would eat it
right -- what
would you do?

46:17.908 --> 46:19.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHILD: I would wait a little
while.

46:19.810 --> 46:22.179 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Could you wait?

46:22.213 --> 46:28.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHILD: Yes. I would play with my
LEGOs. If
there was a fire, I would just
cook it.

46:28.919 --> 46:34.358 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Well, no
marshmallow toasting
in the actual experiment. Kids
were left alone

46:34.392 --> 46:39.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
